<TITLE> PM, theatre world condole playwright Sayeed Ahmad's passing </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 21 (bdnews24.com)  Sayeed Ahmad, playwright and teacher of Dhaka University's dramatics and music department, died on Thursday. He was 79. Prime minister Sheikh Hasina expressed her sorrow. Her press secretary, Abul Kalam Azad, told bdnews24.com that the prime minister termed the death an irreparable loss to the country's theatre world. The author and critic is most well-known for his plays Kalbela (1962), Milepost (1965), Trishnae (1968), Ek Din Protidin (1974) and Shesh Nawab (1988), which have been translated into English, French, German and Italian. His works focus on how man is able to confront and survive against the forces of nature and achieve co-existence. Ahmad, born on Jan 1, 1931 in Dhaka, received the Bangla Academy Award in 1975 and the France's highest civilian honour, the Legion d'Honneur, in 1993. "The prime minister prays for peace of the departed soul and expressed her condolences for his grief-stricken family," said Azad. Ahmad died in the capital's Lab Aid Hospital at around 5:50am, Prof Israfil Shaheen of the dramatics department told bdnews24.com. The body was taken to his Lalmatia home from the hospital. It was taken to the Central Shaheed Minar at 1pm for people to pay last respects. He was buried at his family graveyard in Azimpur. Culture minister Abul Kalam Azad and the DU drama department were among those to issue condolence messages. Ahmad through his career delivered lectures at universities and theatre academies around the world, including Brazil, China, France, Germany, Holland, Hong Kong, India, Japan, Malaysia, Morocco, Norway, Thailand, Turkey, USA and the former USSR. He also worked for the BBC Eastern Service during the period 1954-56. bdnews
